  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The International Space Station (ISS) was not launched into space as a single unit. Instead, it was assembled in orbit through the collaboration of multiple space agencies, with components launched over several years beginning in the late 1990s. Here is a brief timeline of the ISS's construction and assembly:\n\n1. **Zarya Module (Functional Cargo Block)**:\n   - Launched on November 20, 1998, by a Russian Proton rocket. Zarya was the first module of the ISS and provided initial power and storage.\n\n2. **Unity Module (Node 1)**:\n   - Launched on December 4, 1998, aboard the Space Shuttle Endeavour on the STS-88 mission. Unity served as the first of the connecting nodes of the ISS.\n\n3. **Zvezda Service Module**:\n   - Launched on July 12, 2000, by a Russian Proton rocket. Zvezda became the main living quarters for astronauts and housed life support systems.\n\n4. **Additional Modules and Construction**:\n   - Over the following years, many more modules were added, launched by various rockets and Space Shuttle missions. Key additions included the Destiny Laboratory Module (2001), the Quest Joint Airlock (2001), the Harmony Node (2007), and many others.\n\nThe ISS construction involved more than a decade of assembly activities in space, with contributions from NASA (United States), Roscosmos (Russia), JAXA (Japan), ESA (European Space Agency), and CSA (Canadian Space Agency). As of 2011, with the addition of the Permanent Multipurpose Module and other components, the ISS was essentially completed, although upgrades and maintenance continue regularly.\n\nThe assembly of the ISS represents one of the most significant international collaborations in space exploration, with operations and contributions ongoing.",
